<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25178k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25178k">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25178k"> 178(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> panjob</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Although the original justice of the Persians began to give place to cruelty and tyranny under Xerxes, and although rebellions, fomented by the Greeks, occurred later in Phoenicia and in Egypt, the Persian empire remained unshaken for two centuries, until the appearance of Alexander of Macedon. In wealth, in religion, and in organisation, it excelled that of Assyria, and in extent it became greater when, after 516 B.C, Darius I. added to his dominions a new province in the <mark>Panjab</mark>. <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 98-9</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The Punjab (also spelled Panjab, the land of &ldquo;five rivers&rdquo;) is a geographical and cultural region in the northern part of the Indian subcontinent. It comprises areas of eastern Pakistan and northern India. As it was never a political unit, its boundaries are ill-defined.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c14120b" href="c14all.htm#c14120b">VI.C.14:120(b)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
